{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_doxa_ver01/data/sn94060041/00542866834/1938032501/0142.xml":{"full_text":"pnmsula Enterprise\nAwarded Rheme Certificate In 1934 for Best General\nM.lr. Up and In 1935 and 1937 for Beat Handling\nDisplay Advertising of All Virginia Weeklies\n\u25a0saber. National Editorial Association, Virginia Press\nAssociation, Virginia Press Circulation\nAudit Bureau\nFounded by\nJOHN W. EDMONDS\nJune 36, 1881\nALFRED B. G. EDMONDS\nJOHN W. EDMONDS, Jr,\nOwners and Publishers\nACCOMAC COURT HOUSE, VA.\nEntered at the Postoffice at Accsmac C. H., Va., as\nSecond-class Matter\nFRIDAY, MARCH 25, 1938\nBIGGEST POWER IN EUROPE\nWhatever one may think of Adolph Hitler,\nit has to be admitted that he has made himself\nthe biggest power in Europe. The startling\n\u25a0events through which he moved the German\narmies over into Austria in defiance of warn\nings and threats and annexed that country,\nprove him to be a man of power with whom\nthe world has to reckon.\nAbout five years ago, when Hitler's Nazi\nparty gained power in Germany, that country\nwas plunged into the depths of misery, despair\nand humiliation. It was subject to the military\npower of France, its army was limited in num\nbers, and it was without resources to defend\nitself against assault. The country was in the\ndepths of economic poverty, with great masses\nof people unable to find employment.\nToday, while it has not fully assembled the\nmilitary equipment it would need for a big\nwar, it may be on the whole, considering the:\nenthusiasm and man power behind it, the\ngreatest military power in Europe. The coun\ntry has recovered its feeling of independence\nand has escaped from its old humiliation and\ndefeat. Now it spreads out and enlarges its\nboundaries and no one knows where it will stop.\nIt is doubtful if there is in all history a\ncase of a country that has gone in such a\nshort time from such a state of despair to\none of great power. The rise of France, when\nNapoleon Bonaparte became the ruler of that\ncountry about 140 years ago, might be com\npared to it, but it did not come so suddenly,\nnor from such a condition of prostration.\nIt is not surprising that the German people,\nor a majority of them, seem to adore Hitler\nas a kind of savior and almost worship him.\nHis daring audacity makes the world tremble\nfor fear of what he will do next. The Amer\nican people should have learned by their ex\nperience in the World War that they accomplish\nno good by interfering with Europe's quarrels.\n'Jfi\nTHAT TV A JACKASS\nIn a recent speech in the Senate attacking\nthe Tennessee Valley Authority and demand\ning a Congressional investigation of its waste\nful activities. Senator H. Styles Bridges of New\nHampshire told of the now famous jackass\nwhich he said cost the TV A 84.500 and was\nsold for $350 after proving unsatisfactory.\nBridges said a TV A committee spent\n$2,080 for travel expenses searching for a per\nfect jackass in Kentucky, Missouri and Ten\nnessee, finally buying one near Columbia, Tenn.,\nfor $2,500, thus being out a total of $4,500 in\nobtaining the animal. Then, said the Senator:\n\u201cCame the spring, the season of daffodils\nand young love. Romance blossomed on the\nbroad meadows of the Tennessee Valley, but\nTVA\u2019s jackass just wasn\u2019t interested. The ex\nperts foregathered, shook their heads and de\ncided to sell the jackass. They got $300 for\nMm from one J. B. Waters in Sevier County,\na net loss to TVA of $4,280.\u201d\nSince Senator Bridges made the foregoing\nstatement, Mr. Waters told the Associated\nPress that he really paid the TVA $350 for\nthe animal, but that it had died several months\nago.\nIt would be interesting to know whether\nthe loss on this investment was charged to\nnavigation, flood control, power or plain jack\nassery.\n\nAMERICA IN A ROUGH WORLD\nSecretary of State Hull took fairly strong\nground in his recent address, about the attitude\nof the United States toward international law\nlessness. He condemned the countries that\nbreak treaties and held that the United States\nmust adopt \u201cparallel action\u201d with governments\nwhose ideas are similar to ours.\nOur people hate and condemn the treaty\nbreaking that is now common. \u201cParallel action\u201d\nis a phrase that might be stretched by some\nalong a path down which America does not\ncare to go. If parallel action meant, in case\nGreat Britain goes to war over the aggressions\nof Germany, that the United States should also\ndo warlike things, our people would say, \u201cno.\u201d\nThe action of America in the World War\nwas paid for by a terrific price, and when the\nprice was paid, the world was worse off than\nbefore.\n\n\u201cGermany Stuns World\u201d\u2014headline. Which\nseems to have become a habit.\n\nSome display great will power, while others\nannoy us by demonstrating their won\u2019t power. I\nTHE WORLD\u2019S CRUELTY\nIs the world growing more cruel Do\npeople like to see others suffer? Or are many\nso hardened that they don\u2019t care a rap whether\nothers suffer or not, provided they accomplish\nthe things they want?\nIt used to seem as if humane sentiment\nwere making great progress. The boys were\ntaught not to stone the dogs and the birds.\nThey were instructed not to tie the tin dipper\nto Tige\u2019s tail, nor to pull Old Pussy\u2019s whiskers.\nAll over the land we see hospitals doing their\nsuperb work of mercy. Societies to protect\nchildren watch over those who are beaten or\nneglected by harsh parents.\nThere is another side to the picture, even\nin our own advanced country. Gangsters and\ngunmen rarely show humane sentiment. Kid\nnapping would flourish largely in spite of the\nagonies of parents and friends, were it not for\nthe vigilance of the government and police.\nIn other lands it seems cruelty is worse\nthan for many centuries. Around 1000 people\nwere killed in poor Barcelona in Spain the other\nday. when the bombers roared over that city,\ncasting shells into the midst of the terror\nstricken population. Similar scenes have been\nwitnessed in China.\nIn Russia, one can only guess the number\nof the vast multitude who have either been\nlined up against a wall and shot, or have been\nsent to cold climates for exile at hard labor,\nwhere death seemed the probable result. The;\nGerman annexation of Austria is not so blood\nthirsty, but many Jews have been arrested mid\nbeaten, others are committing suicide and many\nwill be deprived of their means of earning a\nliving. What has become of the world\u2019s hu\nmanity? Did the World War raise a genera\ntion of people who do not care how much others\nare made to suffer?\n\nSPENDING AND DEBT\nThoughtful citizens are wondering how\nlong the present rate of government spending\ncan be continued without a serious impairment\nof the national credit. All talk, even, of a'\nbalanced budget has practically ceased, although\na year or so ago it was predicted in high places\nthat the national expenditures would be held\nwithin the national income by 1939.\nRelief expenditures alone for the present\nyear, ending June 30, will be $1,750,000,000,'\nwhich is more than the entire national debt\nprior to the World War. The national debt is,\napproaching the 40 billion dollar mark, or about\n\u00a7300 for every man, woman and child in the\nLnited States. When to this we add the enor\nmous debts of state and local governments,1\nwith nearly all being steadily increased, the\nburden is staggering.\nIt is true that we are not yet as deeply in\ndebt per capita as several other countries, but\nwith more billions being added continually, the\ndebt problem is becoming serious. The funds\nderived from social security taxes are being\nused for current expenses, and this device has\nserved to slightly ease the strain on the treas\nury. although in reality it is increasing the\ngovernment\u2019s obligations just the same.\nThe debt situation should not be considered\nfrom a partisan political point of view, but as\na problem to be seolved through the cooperation\nof all officials and citizens. It is evident that1\nthere is something wrong with policies which\npermit such a situation to continue and grow\nworse.\nX\nNOTES ON BUSINESS\nDiscussions regarding the business outlook\ndisclose differences of opinion among supposed\nexperts and whether the bottom of the new\ndepression has been reached is difficult to de-;\ntermine. Many believe that a moderate upturn\nmay occur soon, but all agree that recovery will\nbe slow.\nDuring the first week in March trading on\nthe New York Stock Exchange was the smallest\nthat has been recorded for any week without\na holiday-since May, 1924.\nAutomobile shipments in February were,\n47 per cent below those of February, 1937, and;\nthe lowest since September, 1935. Food is'\nrunning about 17 per cent below last year\u2019s!\nsales and department store business is off about j\n8 per cent.\nDuring 1937 the total market value of all I\nstocks listed on the New York Stock Exchange'\nj dropped 36 per cent, and there have been fur-j\nI ther declines since.\nLumber production showed some increase\nI last month, but is still below the output of a\nyear ago. One of the few manufacturing lines\nshowing an increase over the first months of\ni 1937 is farm implements, up about 15 per cent.\n\nUNCLE SAM VS. THE BUGS\nThe government is in for a grand fight\nj with insect pests during the coming summer.\nDroughts and mild winters are called favorable\nto the growth of these nasty critters.\nSome people may say crop surpluses make\nno end of trouble for the farmers, so they\nj should worry if the pests keep these surpluses\ndown. The pests don\u2019t do their work fairly.\nThey allow some districts to raise so much that\nprices go way down, while the product of other\ndistricts is wiped out and the farmers ruined.\nSo a destructive pest is still the enemy of man\nkind. Perhaps if the nation had not tolerated\nthe shooting of birds so easily, these bugs\nwould not sweep over the land as an almost\nuncontrollable force.\nHe Kn\u00a9ius Gv\u20acrythhig~\nLoujRsnc* UfluJTHORne 05J1,\nMy dad knows more than any other man I ever saw\nAbout the way this Country should be run!\nHe knows just when an\u2019 why they oughter make another law. 3\nHe knows how tax reduction should be done.\nHe always trios a murder case buffore the jury does,\nAn\u2019 knows just what the verdic\u2019 oughter be\u2014\nBut when he tries t' start the car, an\u2019 doesn't get a buz2,\nHe always yells fer Mother, or fer me!\nMy dad could be a bigger business-man than Henry Ford,\nAn' make more money, if he wanted to!\nIf he was in a bank, he'd be the Chairman of the Board,\n\u2019Cause he knows jus\u2019 what bankers oughter do;\nHe\u2019d be a better doctor than the smartes\u2019 in the land;\nThe preachers would be pikers, too! But, gee,\nThere ain\u2019t a thing about our car that he can understand,\nSo he depends on Mother, or on me!\nMy dad could manage all the schools and colleges jus\u2019 right,\nAn\u2019 publish all the magazines an\u2019 books.\nHe knowB how women oughter dress fer momin\u2019, noon or night.\nAn\u2019 what each one should do t\u2019 help her looks!\nMy dad knows more than any other man, without a doubt\u2014\n(If you could hear him talk, you\u2019d soon agree!)\nBut when he parks the ear somewhere an\u2019 wants t\u2019 get it out,\nHe hands the job t\u2019 Mother, or t\u2019 me!\nWestern Newspaper Union.\nNews Of Other Years\n50 Years Ago\nMarch 17, 1SS8\nMr. O. P. T. Ewell and wife,\nguests of Dr. A. D. F. Ewell and\nwife, of Leemont, for several months,\nreturn to their home in Kansas,\nnext Monday.\nMrs. Hettie Dix, an estimable lady,\nmother of Mr. Wm. H. Bloxom, died\nat the home of her son. near Bloxom\nStation, on Wednesday, 7th inst.\naged S5 years.\nRev. John McXabb will preach at1\nthe usual hour tomorrow morning\nat St. James Church, Drummond\ntown, and in the afternoon at Jen-1\nkins Bridge, weather permitting.\nA new postoffice has been establish\ned at Barnes Mason\u2019s store, about\ntwo miles from Bloxom\u2019s Station,\nto be known as Gargatha with Mr.\nE. W. Barnes at postmaster.\nThe novel experiment was made\nby several farmers in the vicinity of\nthis town of attempting to retain\nthe heat in their potato beds by the\nuse of lamps. With what success,\nwe are not advised, but our mer\nchants are at least happy, in having\nfound purchasers for all their stock\nin that line.\nWe are cordially informed that\nsuits will be instituted at an early\ndate by the Attorney for the Com\nmonwealth against all parties who\nhave tendered coupons in payment of\ntaxes in the county, of Accomack.\nIf you do not want to be sued, with\ndraw your coupons and pay in money.\nSykes Island is to have a daily\nmail to be supplied from Oak Hall.\nThe route between the two points is\nto be by Jenkins Bridge and San\nford and bids for the privilege of\ncarrying it are now in order. Many\nof our people are so fond of work\ning for the Government, we presume,\nthat in this instance as in many\nothers, some one will be found will\ning to take the contract for barely\nenough to furnish them with \u201cwid\neles and clothes\u201d.\nDuring the late storm the smoke\nstack of steam-mill of Mr. A. J.\nLilliston was blown down with a\nloss to him of $15 or more and an\nunfinished dwelling of Mr. James\nLewis was moved some six or seven\nfeet from its foundation, which can\nbe placed in position again for a\nfew dollars. The damages in other\nrespects in town and vicinity were\nslight. A few trees only were blown\nI down, fences scattered, etc., though\nthe storm seems to have raged with\nj equal fury here as at other points.\nThe dwellings of several of our cit\nizens were so badly shaken by the\nI wind that many complained of feel\ning Monday morning, as if they had\nbeen tossed to and fro by the\nwaves and said they had the sea\nsickness incident to same.\nMetompkin\nMr. J. L. Moore, a spry young\nwidower of Delaware, has been en\ngaged as clerk by an enterprising\nmerchant, Mr. Charles R. Byrd.\nThe lumber is being cut for a\nhandsome dwelling to be erected by\nMr. J. F. Wessells this spring, and\nthe young man it is said is open\nfor leap year proposals.\nMiss Estelle Watts was a guest\nof Misses Lillie and Maggie White\nlast week. Another of our attractive\nyoung ladies, Miss Margie Wessells\nhas returned from a short visit to\nfriends at Powellton.\nThe blizzard of last Sunday and\ni Monday did considerable damage in\nj this section. Fences were blown\nI down, hundreds of valuable trees\ntom up by the roots, potato bed\nframes scattered in every direction\nand broken, and one house toppled\nover making a wreck of valuable\ncarriage of Mrs. M. J. White. Messrs.\nB. F. Parks and Robert W. Hick\nman, each had about 3 boxes of\nglass broken and many frames de\nstroyed. Many other farmers suf\nfered loss, more or less.\nOur Church (Zion) is now in a\nflourishing condition. Services are\nheld there regularly every Sunday\nconducted by the pastor, Rev. J. S.\nWharton. On last Sunday morning\nthe Sabbath School was thoroughly\nre-organized and following officers\nelected: Wm. F. White, superintend\nent; George F. Parks, assistant;\nJudson F. Wessells, secretary; J.\nMorgan Dix, librarian; George D.\nWise, assistant; Zadoc Mason, treas\nurer; Wm. Parks, assistant; A. F.\nWessells, supervisor; Miss Mamie\nByrd, organist; Miss Annie Fox, as\nsistant.\n\nGreenbackville\nIt is now (Wednesday) quite cold\nhere. The ground is thickly coated\nwith snow and the thermometer in\ndicates only 18 degrees above zero.\nJester\u2019s Chapel, a new M. P.\nChurch edifice near this place, was\ndedicated last Sunday. Rev. A. D.\nTrelain, of Pocomoke City, Md.,\npreached tilt dedicatory sermon to\na large audience. The contributions\non the occasion amounted to $325\na sum sufficient to pay off claims\nj and demands against said church.\nX'o mail was received here from\nany point on last Monday in conse\nquence of the inclement weather.\nThe train bringing our mail from\nthe north on that day was \u201csnow\ned in\u2019\u2019 at a point near Lewes, Del.,\nand an engine was sent from this\nplace to her relief. The mail and\npassengers arrived at Franklin City,\nTuesday.\nConsiderable damage to shipping\nis reported here, and a rumor is cur\nrent today (Wednesday), that 13\npersons in attempting to escape from\na sinking vessel landing on a pier\nwhich had been severed from the\nmainland at Lewes, Del., to find\nthemselves beyond the reach of as\nsistance and were frozen to death.\nOnancock\nCapt. Hayward B. Keaton is ser\niously ill at his home near our town\nand is not expected to recover.\nMr. Upshur Broughton has been\nappointed postmaster at Onancock,\nto fill the vacancy caused by the\ndeath of Capt. Stephen Hopkins.\nMessrs. Powell Waples, Fosque\nCo., W. D. Lewis, Hopkins\nBro. (of whom mention is made\nelsewhere) each were damaged by\nthe late storm from $25 to $50.\nOur townsman, Mr. Smith Walter,\nis now at Jacksonville, Florida. He\nleft Baltimore for that point about\n10 days ago on a handsome three\nmasted schooner as a passenger and\nthe guest of Capt. Len Tawes, her\ncommander.\nThe lumber has been ordered for\na large and handsome building to be\nerected this spring on the corner lot\nrecently purchased by Mr. E. E.\nMiles, opposite store of W. D. Lewis.\nIt will be large enough and it is\nproposed to subdivide it into three\n1 business houses.\nCapt. Thomas Johnson has gone\nI on a tour north, and when last\n1 heard from was at Buffalo, N. Y.\nThe captain makes the trip princi\npally for pleasure, but it is said will\ncombine a little business with it, and\nhe .expects to purchase a tugboat\nbefore his return, if he can find one\n1 to suit, to ply between this place and\nTangier Island. In the event of the\npurchase, Capt. Wm. F. Rogers is to\n1 be captain of the tug.\nl\nBelle Haven\nSixteen drummers passed through\nj our town one day last week, and\nmany knights of the grip sought\nshelter at Doughtys hotel in our\ntown during the storm.\nf Continued on page 14\nNarcissus Show\nAt Onancock\nI March 30th\nContinued from page 1\nB\u2014Bi-color varieties with white or\nwhitish perianth and self-yellow, red\nstained on cup. 1. Single specimen.\n2. Vase of three stalks, one variety.\n3. Collection, one stalk of each va\nriety.\nIV. Leedsii: Perianth white, cup\nwhite, cream or pale citron, some\ntimes tinged with pink or apricot.\nDivision A\u2014Cup not less than one\nthird but less than equal to the\nlength of perianth segments. I.\nSingle specimen. 2. Vase of three\nstalks, one variety. 3. Collection,\none stalk of each variety. Division\nB\u2014Cup less than one-third the\nlength of perianth segments. 1.\nSingle specimen. 2. Vase of three\nstalks, one variety. 3. Collection,\none stalk of each variety.\nV. Triandrus Hybrids: Varieties of\nNarcissus Triandrus parentage. Di\nvision A\u2014Cup not less than one\nthird but less than equal to the\nlength of perianth segments. 1.\nSingle specimen. 2. Vase of three\nstalks, one variety. 3. Collection,\none stalk of each variety. Division\nB\u2014Cup less than one-third the length\nof perianth segments. 1. Single\nspecimen. 2. Vase of three stalks,\none variety. 3. Collection, one stalk\nof each variety.\nVI. Jonquilla Hybrids: Varieties\nof Narcissus Jonquilla parentage.\n1. Single specimen. 2. Vase of\nthree stalks, one variety. 3. Collec\ntion, one stalk of each variety.\nVII. Poetaz (Tazetta Hybrids):\nSeveral short-cupped flowers to a\nstem. 1. Single specimen. 2. Vase\nof three stalks. 3. Collection, one\nstalk of each variety.\nVIII. Poeticus: White perianth\nsegments, flattened cup, yellow or\nlemon, red-stained edge, or solid\nred. 1. Single specimen. 2. Vase\nof three stalks, one variety. 3. Col\nlection, one stalk of each variety.\nIX. Double Narcissi: 1. Single\nspecimens 2. Vase of three stalks,\none variety. 3. Collection, one stalk\nof each variety. 1\nSpecial Classes I\nX. Trumpets and Leedsii: All\nwhite varieties. Collection, one stalk\neach.\nI XI. Incomparabilis and Barrii:\nI Yellow perianth with red or partially\nI red cup. Collection, one stalk each, j\nXII. Incomparabilis and Barrii:\nWith white perianth. Collection, one\nstalk each.\nXIII. Jonquilla and Triandrus Hy\nbrids. Collection, one stalk each.\nThe scale of points for classes I\nto XIII inclusive of Narcissi adopted\nby Royal Horticultural Society are:\nForm, 25; Substance, 25; Color, 20;\nSize of bloom, 16; Length of stem,\n15; Total 100.\nArrangements\nNarcissi Predominating\nXIV. Yellow Narcissi with other\nflowers in tones of cream, yellow or\nbrown, in amber glass container.\nXV. Narcissi with other flowers\nand shrubs.\nXVI. White Narcissi with other\nwhite flowers and green foliage in\nclear glass or all white contained\nSpace allowed: 22 inches wide by It\ninches deep by 27 inches high.\nXVII. Miniature Narcissi with\nother spring flowering bulbs of like\nsize.\nXVIII. Arrangement in white pot\ntery.\nXIX. Arrangement in green pot\ntery.\nXX. Arrangement in any color pot\ntery.\nXXI. Arrangement in wood.\nXXII. Arrangement in pewter.\nXXIII. Arrangement in copper.\nXXIV. Arrangement in large pitch\ners.\nXXV. Arrangement in small pitch\ners.\nXXVI. Arrangement in clear glass.\nYouth Program At\nBethel Baptist Church\nSunday, March 27\nBethel Baptist Church will take1\npart in the observance of Youth\nWeek by having a special service for\nyouths Sunday morning, March 27,\ni at 11 o\u2019clock. The special program\nwill consist of special music ren\ndered by the young people\u2019s choir\nand a special sermon for youth by\nthe pastor, Rev. Scott C. Hutton.\nBefore the preaching hour there\nwill be a special Missionary pro\ngram given by the young people of\nthe Sunday School. The public is\ncordially invited to these services.\nST. JAMES AND EMMANUEL\nEPISCOPAL CHURCHES\nThomas S. Forbes, Rector\nSunday, March 27th, 1938\nSt. James, Accomac\nMorning prayer and sermon 11\na. m.\nEmmanuel, Jenkins Bridge\nEvening prayer and sermon 3 p.\nm.\nWednesday afternoon, March 30th\nSt. James Parish House, evening\nprayer and Litany 3 p. m.\nEnglish Program\nGiven Tuesday\nA meeting of the Educational De\npartment of the Woman\u2019s Club of\nAccomack County was held at the\nresidence of Mrs. F'mer Littleton, at\nModestown, Tuesday evening, March\n22.\nChurch Notices\nPARKSLEY AND ZION BAPTIST\nCHURCHES\nRev. John H. Allen, Pastor\nSunday, March 27, 1938\nZion and Parksley Baptist Chur\nches will be led in the morning\nworship, Sunday, March 27, by two\nministers from Crozer Seminary,\nChester, Pa., who will be guests in\nthe home of the pastor and family\nfor the week-end.\nWorship service at Zion will be\ngin at 10 a. m., as usual. The scrip\nture lesson will be read and prayer\noffered by Dr. R. E. E. Harkness,\nprofessor of Church History at the\nseminary. The sermon, \u201cGreen Pas\ntures\u2019\u2019 will be delivered by Kenneth\nLloyd Garrison, head of deputation\nwork.\nThe service at Parksley will be at\n11:30 a. m. with Dr. Harkness\npreaching.\nMr. Garrison was born at Kings\nton, N. Y., received his college\ntraining at Georgetown College, Ky.,\nwas assistant pastor at the Lans\ndowne Baptist Church, Lansdowne,\nPa., during last year. His work was\nmostly with young people. As chair\nman of deputation work his week\nends are spent in visiting churches\nin the eastern states.\nDr Harkness was born in Ontario,\nCanada. He holds a Ph. D. from the\nUniversity of Chicago, has held pas\ntorates in Illinois and Wisconsin\nstates, and is now president of the\nAmerican Baptist Historical Soci\nety and professor of Church History\nat the Seminary.\nThe pastor enjoys supreme delight\nin presenting these friends to the:\ncommunity and in extending a cord\nial invitation to all to come and hear\nthem.\nQuinby\nMr. and Mrs. Robert Harris and\nchildren visited relatives at Painter,\nSunday.\nMr. Carroll Marshall, of C. C. C.\ncamp, is visiting his mother, Mrs.\nW. A. Tarr.\nMr. Alden Corbin, of Onley, spent,\nthe week-end with his family and:\nparents here.\nMessrs. Harry White and Edward\nWilson visited friends at Wacha\npreague, Saturday.\nMrs. A. R. Letteri and son, of\nOnancoek, spent Monday with her\nmother, Mrs. J. O. Wallace.\nMrs. J. C. Ward has returned\nhome, after spending several days,\nwith her daughter, at Exmore\nMrs. G. W. Mears, of Keller,\nwhile on a visit with her daugh\nter, Mrs. Clarence Kellam, died sud\ndenly, Friday morning.\nMr. and Mrs. Leslie Taylor and\nchildren, of Chincoteague, spent Sun\nday with Mrs. Taylor's parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. L. T. Cropper.\nMr. Otho Ivillmon and Mrs. Way\nmon Killmon anil two children, of\nBridgetown and Mr .and Mrs. Le\nland Corbin, of Wachapreague, spent\nSunday with Mr. and Mrs. T. H.\nBudd. Mrs. Trader and Mrs. An\nthony were callers in the home Sat\nurday.\nDeaths\nMr. Ward K. Hyslop\nMr. Ward K. Hyslop, a retired\nfarmer and a highly esteemed cit\nizen, passed away at his home at\nCraddockville, Va., Wednesday, March\n-3rd, aged 74 years. He had been\nill for several weeks and his death\nwas not unexpected. Mr. Hyslop was\nan upright citizen, a devoted and\nI consistent member of the Methodist\nj Church and a sincere friend. His\npassing is lamented by a host of\nj relatives and friends in lower Accor\nmack.\nFuneral services were held at\nCraddockville Methodist Church, of\nwhich he was a member of the Board\nof Stewards, on Thursday,. March.\n24th, conducted by his pastor, Rev.\nA. J. Carter and interment was in\nBelle Haven Cemetery.\nThe active pallbearers were Messrs\nOtho Custis, Clyde Hutchinson, Byrd\nKellam, George Duer, Willard Phil\nlips and Russell Floyd. The honorary\npallbearers were Messrs. Duncan\nMears, Will Mears, Henry Martin,\nForrest Davis, Edward Bull, Edgar\nParks, Richard Floyd, K. C. Rice,\nTank Kellam, Leonard Hutchinson,\nOswald Selby, Barton Nelson, Lee\nKellam, John Davis, Norman Kel\nlam, Nottingham Smith, Omar Kel\nlam, Roy Kellam, John Ames, L.\nB. Smith, Dorsey Mears, J. E. Drum\nmond, M. S. Kellam, R. B. Custis,\nT. G. Custis, H. E. Custis, J. T.\nMelson and Will Copes.\nHe is survived by a daughter,.\nMrs. H. Dana Custis, of Craddock\u2014\nville, two sons, Messrs. John Smith\nHyslop and W. Finney Hyslop, or\nnear Pungoteague, five grandchil\ndren, Miss Tracy King Custis, Miss\nMargaret Hyslup, Miss Anne Bull,\nMessrs. John Smith Hyslop, Jr. and!\nFred Floyd, Jr., and a sister, Mrs.\nGeorge Starkey, of Norfolk, Va.\nBrief but interesting sketches were\ngiven of the lives of John Masefield,\nPoet I-aureate of England by Miss\nLena Johnson, and of William Glad\nstone by Mrs. Richard Taylor. Fol\nlowing these, and in keeping with the\nall-English program Mrs. .7. S. Ledger\nvery capably reviewed the play \u201cVic\ntoria Regina\u201d.","height":"26580","width":"19772"}}
